'''Pedro II''' ({{IPA-pt|<U+02C8>ped<U+027E>u}}; English: Peter II; 2 December 1825 &ndash; 5 December 1891), nicknamed "the [[Magnanimity|Magnanimous]]",<ref name="Bueno, p.196">[[#refBueno2003|Bueno (2003)]], p. 196.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 85.</ref> was the [[List of Brazilian monarchs#Emperors of Brazil (1822<U+2013>1889) - post-Independence monarchs of the Brazilian Empire|second and last ruler]] of the [[Empire of Brazil]], reigning for over 58 years.{{ref label|specialnote_A|A|none}} His name in full was '''Pedro de Alc<U+00E2>ntara Jo<U+00E3>o Carlos Leopoldo Salvador Bibiano Francisco Xavier de Paula Leoc<U+00E1>dio Miguel Gabriel Rafael Gonzaga''' (English: Peter of Alcantara John Charles Leopold Saviour Vivian Francis Xavier of Paula Leocadio Michael Gabriel Raphael Gonzaga).<ref name="Bueno, p.196"/><ref name="Vainfas, p.198">[[#refVainfas2002|Vainfas (2002)]], p. 198.</ref><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.4">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 4.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 45.</ref> Born in [[Rio de Janeiro]], he was the seventh child of Emperor Dom [[Pedro I of Brazil]] and [[Maria Leopoldina of Austria|Empress Maria Leopoldina]] and thus a member of the Brazilian branch of the [[House of Braganza]], and was referred to using the honorific "[[Dom (title)|Dom]]" from birth.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 424.</ref> His father's abrupt abdication and flight to Europe in 1831 left a 5-year-old Pedro as Emperor and led to a grim and lonely childhood and adolescence. Obliged to spend his time studying in preparation for rule, he knew only brief moments of happiness and encountered few friends of his age. His experiences with court intrigues and political disputes during this period greatly affected his later character. Pedro II grew into a man with a strong sense of duty and devotion toward his country and his people. On the other hand, he increasingly resented his role as monarch.

Inheriting an empire on the verge of disintegration, Pedro II turned [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]-speaking [[Brazil]] into an emerging power in the international arena. The nation grew to be distinguished from its [[Hispanic America|Hispanic neighbors]] on account of its political stability, zealously-guarded freedom of speech, respect for civil rights, vibrant economic growth and especially for its form of government: a functional, [[Constitutional monarchy|representative parliamentary monarchy]]. Brazil was also victorious in three international conflicts (the [[Platine War]], the [[Uruguayan War]] and the [[War of the Triple Alliance]]) under his rule, as well as prevailing in several other international disputes and domestic tensions. Pedro steadfastly pushed through the abolition of slavery despite opposition from powerful political and economic interests. A savant in his own right, the Emperor established a reputation as a vigorous sponsor of learning, culture and the sciences. He won the respect and admiration of scholars such as [[Charles Darwin]], [[Victor Hugo]] and [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], and was a friend to [[Richard Wagner]], [[Louis Pasteur]] and [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]], among others.

Although there was no desire for a change in the form of government among most [[Brazilian people|Brazilians]], the Emperor was overthrown in a sudden coup d'<U+00E9>tat that had almost no support outside a clique of military leaders who desired a form of [[republic]] headed by a [[Dictatorship|dictator]]. Pedro II had become weary of emperorship and despaired over the monarchy's future prospects, despite its overwhelming popular support. He allowed no prevention of his ouster and did not support any attempt to restore the monarchy afterwards. He spent the last two years of his life in exile in Europe, living alone on very little money.

The reign of Pedro II thus came to an unusual end<U+2014>he was overthrown while highly regarded by the people and at the pinnacle of his popularity, and most of his accomplishments were soon brought to naught as Brazil slipped into a long period of anarchy, dictatorship and economic crises. The same men who had exiled him soon began to see in him a model for the Brazilian republic. A few decades after his death, his reputation was restored and his remains were returned to Brazil as those of a national hero. This reputation has lasted to the present day. Historians have regarded the Emperor in an extremely positive light, and he is usually ranked as the greatest Brazilian ever.

==Early life==
{{Main|Early life of Pedro II of Brazil}}

===Birth===
[[File:Pedro II 1826.jpg|thumb|left|180px|alt=Framed oval head and shoulders portrait of a an infant boy|Pedro II at 10 months old, 1826]]
Pedro was born at 2:30&nbsp;a.m. on 2 December 1825 in the [[Pa<U+00E7>o de S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o|Palace of S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o]], located in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref name="Besouchet, p.39">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 39.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 11<U+2013>12.</ref><ref name="Olivieri, p.5">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 5.</ref> His name was a homage to St. [[Peter of Alcantara]].<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 3.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 46.</ref> Through his father, Emperor [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro I]], he was a member of the Brazilian branch of the [[House of Braganza]]. He was the grandson of Portuguese King [[John VI of Portugal|Jo<U+00E3>o VI]] and nephew of [[Miguel of Portugal|Miguel I]].<ref name="Besouchet, p.40">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 40.</ref><ref name="Schwarcz, p.47">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 47.</ref> His mother was the Archduchess [[Maria Leopoldina of Austria]], daughter of [[Francis II, Holy Roman Emperor|Franz II]], the last [[Holy Roman Emperor]]; through his mother, Pedro was a nephew of [[Napoleon I|Napoleon Bonaparte]] and first cousin of Emperors [[Napoleon II of France]], [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] and [[Maximilian I of Mexico]].<ref name="Schwarcz, p.47"/><ref name="Barman 1999, p.1">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 1.</ref><ref name="Besouchet, p.41">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 41.</ref>

The only legitimate male child of Pedro I to survive infancy, he was officially recognized as heir to the Brazilian throne with the title Prince Imperial on 6 August 1826.<ref name="Vainfas, p.198"/><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.5">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 5.</ref> Empress Leopoldina died on 11 December 1826, a few days following the stillbirth of a male child,<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 15.</ref> when Pedro was a year old.<ref name="Besouchet, p.41"/> Pedro would have no memory of his mother apart from what he was later told about her.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.13">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 13.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 16.</ref> The memory and influence of his father also faded, and by the time he was an adult, "he retained no strong images of him".<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 22.</ref>

Two and a half years after the death of Leopoldina, the Emperor married [[Am<U+00E9>lie of Leuchtenberg]]. Prince Pedro spent little time with his stepmother; nevertheless, they had an affectionate relationship<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.16">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 16.</ref><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 46.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 26.</ref> and kept contact until her death in 1873.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 20.</ref> Emperor Pedro I abdicated on 7 April 1831, after a long conflict with the [[Liberalism in Brazil|liberal faction]] (which itself later split into what would become the two dominant parties under the monarchy: the Conservative and the Liberal parties). He and Am<U+00E9>lie immediately departed for Europe to [[Liberal Wars|restore his daughter to the Portuguese throne]], which had been usurped by his brother Miguel I.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.21">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 21.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 15.</ref> Left behind, Prince Imperial Pedro became ''Dom Pedro II, Constitutional Emperor and Perpetual Defender of Brazil''.<ref name="Olivieri, p.5"/>

===Education===
[[File:RetratodompedroIIcrianca.JPG|thumb|200px|right|alt=Three-quarters length painted portrait of the pre-adolescent Pedro in gold-embroidered tunic with sash of office and hat tucked under his right arm and left hand resting on the pommel of his sword|Emperor Pedro II at age 12 wearing the court dress uniform of an Admiral and the Order of the Golden Fleece, 1838]] 
Upon leaving the country, Emperor Pedro I selected three people to [[Minority reign|take charge]] of his son and remaining daughters. The first was [[Jos<U+00E9> Bonif<U+00E1>cio de Andrada e Silva|Jos<U+00E9> Bonif<U+00E1>cio]], his friend and an influential leader during Brazilian independence, who was named guardian.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.17">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 17.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 50.</ref> The second was Mariana de Verna, who had held the post of ''aia'' ([[Governess|supervisor]]) since the birth of Pedro II.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.31">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 31.</ref> As a child, the Prince Imperial called her "''Dadama''", as he could not pronounce the word ''dama'' ([[Lady]]) correctly.<ref name="Calmon (1975), p.5"/> Pedro II regarded her as his surrogate mother, and would continue to call her by her nickname well into adulthood out of affection.<ref name="Besouchet, p.39"/><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 29.</ref> The third person was Rafael, an [[Afro-Brazilian]] veteran of the [[Argentina-Brazil War]].<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.31"/><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.57">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 57.</ref> Rafael was an employee in the [[Pa<U+00E7>o de S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o|Palace of S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o]] (Pedro II's primary residence from infancy)<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 19.</ref> whom Pedro I deeply trusted and asked to look after his son<U+2014>a charge which he carried out during the rest of his life.<ref name="Vainfas, p.198"/><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.57"/>

Bonif<U+00E1>cio was dismissed from his position in December 1833 and replaced by another guardian.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.57">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 57.</ref><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.25">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 25.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 33.</ref> Pedro II spent his days studying,<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.27">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 27.</ref> with only two hours set aside for amusements.<ref name="Olivieri, p.8">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 8.</ref> He would wake at 6.30&nbsp;a.m. and begin his studies at seven, continuing until 10&nbsp;p.m., after which he would go to bed.<ref name="Vainfas, p.199">[[#refVainfas2002|Vainfas (2002)]], p. 199.</ref> Great care was taken in his education to foster values and a character different from the impulsiveness and irresponsibility which had been displayed by his father.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.57"/><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 56.</ref> His passion for reading allowed him to assimilate any information.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.50">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 50.</ref> Pedro II was no genius,<ref name="Olivieri, p.6">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 6.</ref> but he was intelligent<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 14.</ref> and able to acquire knowledge with great ease.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 46.</ref>

The Emperor experienced an unhappy and solitary childhood.<ref name="Vainfas, p.198"/><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.30">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 30.</ref> The sudden loss of his parents would shadow him later in life;<ref name="Barman 1999, p.33">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 33.</ref> he had few friends of his age,<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.31"/><ref name="Vainfas, p.199"/><ref name="Besouchet, p.50"/> and contact with his sisters was limited.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.57"/><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.27"/><ref name="Besouchet, p.50">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 50.</ref> The environment in which he was raised turned him into a shy and needy person<ref name="Olivieri, p.9">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 9.</ref><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.33">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 33.</ref> who saw books as a refuge and retreat from the real world.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.29">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 29.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 39.</ref>

===Early coronation===
[[File:Manuel de Ara<U+00FA>jo Porto-alegre - estudo para a sagra<U+00E7><U+00E3>o de Dom Pedro II - c. 1840.jpg|thumb|260px|left|alt=Painting showing the crowned emperor standing before the throne in a columned hall and grasping a scepter with a crowd of dignitaries assembled below.|Coronation of Pedro II at age 15, 18 July 1841]]
The elevation of Pedro II to the Imperial throne in 1831 led to a period of crisis, the most troublesome in Brazil's history.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 21.</ref> A [[Regent|regency]] had been created to rule on his behalf until he reached the age of majority.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.21"/> Disputes between political factions led to several rebellions and resulted in an unstable, almost anarchical, situation under the regents.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 53.</ref>

The possibility of lowering the young emperor's age of majority, instead of waiting until he turned 18 on 2 December 1843, had been floated since 1835.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.37">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 37.</ref><ref name="Schwarcz, p.67">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 67.</ref><ref>[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 11.</ref> The idea had received support from both main political parties.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.67"/><ref name="Lyra v.1, p.67">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 67.</ref> It was thought that those assisting him in taking the reins of government would be in a position to manipulate the inexperienced youth.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.38">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 38.</ref> Those politicians who had risen to power during the 1830s had by now also become familiar with the pitfalls of rule. According to historian Roderick J. Barman, by 1840 "they had lost all faith in their ability to rule the country on their own. They accepted Pedro II as an authority figure whose presence was indispensable for the country's survival."<ref name="Barman1999, p.317">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 317.</ref> The Brazilian people also supported lowering the age of majority,<ref>[[#refBueno2003|Bueno (2003)]], pp. 194<U+2013>195.</ref> as they considered Pedro II "the living symbol of the unity of the fatherland"; this position "gave him, in the eyes of public opinion, a higher authority than that of any regent."<ref>[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 10.</ref>

Those advocating the immediate elevation of Pedro II to majority passed a motion requesting the Emperor assume full powers.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.72">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 72.</ref> A delegation was sent to the Palace of S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o to ask whether Pedro II would accept or reject an early declaration of his majority.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.72"/><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.39">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 39.</ref><ref name="Schwarcz, p.68">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 68.</ref> He shyly answered "Yes" when asked if he desired the age of majority to be lowered, and "Now" when asked if he would prefer that it come into effect at that moment or would rather await his birthday in December.<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 136.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 70.</ref> On the following day, 23 July 1840, the ''Assembl<U+00E9>ia Geral'' (the National Assembly) formally declared the 14-year-old Pedro II of age.<ref name="Bueno, p.194">[[#refBueno2003|Bueno (2003)]], p. 194.</ref><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.40">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 40.</ref> There, in the afternoon, the young emperor took the oath of office.<ref name="Olivieri, p.12">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 12.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 73.</ref> He was acclaimed, crowned and consecrated on 18 July 1841.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 73.</ref><ref name="Lyra v.1, p.72">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 72.</ref>

==Consolidation==
{{Main|Consolidation of Pedro II of Brazil}}

===Marriage===
[[File:Teresa cristina 1846.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=Half-length painted portrait of a smiling young woman in early Victorian blue formal gown wearing a blue sash of office over one shoulder|[[Teresa Cristina of the Two Sicilies|Teresa Cristina]], wife of Pedro&nbsp;II, at age 24, 1846]]
Removal of the factious regency stabilized the government. With a legitimate monarch on the throne, authority was vested in a single, clear voice.<ref name="Barman1999 p.74">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 74.</ref> Pedro II perceived his role as that of an arbiter, keeping personal views from hindering his duty to untangle partisan political disputes.<ref name="Barman1999 p.74"/> The young Emperor was diligent in his new role, making daily personal inspections and visits to government branches. His subjects were impressed by his seeming self-confidence,<ref name="Barman1999 p.74"/> although his shyness and lack of social grace were considered flaws. His reticence in only offering a word or two at a time rendered direct conversation with him extremely difficult.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.75">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 75.</ref> His taciturn nature manifested a caution in close relationships that traced to incidents of abandonment, intrigue and betrayal experienced during his childhood.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 66.</ref>

Behind the scenes, a group of high ranking palace servants and notable politicians became known as the "Courtier Faction" as they established influence over the young Emperor<U+2014>and some were very close indeed.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.49">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 49.</ref> Pedro II was deftly used by the courtiers to eliminate their foes (actual or suspected) by obtaining the dismissal of rivals. Access to his person by rival politicians and the flow of information he received were strictly controlled. A continuous round of meetings, study, personal appearances and government business, used as distractions, kept the Emperor occupied, effectively isolating and keeping him unaware of being exploited.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 80.</ref> 

Concerned about the Emperor's taciturnity and immaturity, the courtiers believed marriage would improve his behavior and character.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.93">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 93.</ref> The government of the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]] offered the hand of Princess [[Teresa Cristina of the Two Sicilies|Teresa Cristina]].<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.116">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 116.</ref><ref name="Olivieri, p.17">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 17.</ref><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.203">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 203.</ref> A portrait of Teresa Cristina was sent by the Kingdom to Pedro II, depicting a beautiful young woman and prompting him to accept the match.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], pp. 117<U+2013>119.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 205.</ref> The new Brazilian Empress arrived on 3 September 1843.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.123">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 123.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 238.</ref> Upon seeing her in person, he was noticeably disappointed.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.97">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 97.</ref><ref name="Lyra v.1, p.124">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 124.</ref><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.239">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 239.</ref> The picture he had been sent was an obvious idealization; the real Teresa Cristina was short, a bit overweight, walked with a pronounced limp and though not ugly, neither was she pretty.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.97"/><ref name="Lyra v.1, p.124"/><ref name="Schwarcz, p.95">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 95.</ref> He did little to hide his disillusionment. One observer stated that he turned his back to Teresa Cristina, another depicted him as being so shocked that he needed to sit, and it is possible that both occurred.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.97"/> That evening, Pedro II wept and complained to Mariana de Verna, "They have deceived me, ''Dadama''!"<ref name="Barman 1999, p.97"/><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.239"/><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.52">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 52.</ref> It took several hours to convince him that duty demanded that he proceed.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.97"/><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.239"/><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.52"/> The wedding celebration occurred on the following day, 4 September.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], pp. 125<U+2013>126.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 240.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 98.</ref>

===Imperial authority established===
[[File:Pedro II of Brazil by Rugendas 1846.jpg|thumb|210px|left|alt=Full-length painted portrait of a blond young man standing in a garden dressed in white trousers, a military tunic with heavy gold braid, a blue sash of office, and holding a bicorn admiral's hat|Pedro II, at age 20 wearing the court dress uniform of an admiral, 1846]]
By 1846 Pedro II had matured physically and mentally. He was no longer an insecure 14-year-old swayed by gossip, suggestions of secret plots, and other manipulative tactics.<ref name="Barman1999, p.109">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 109.</ref> He grew into a man who, at {{m to ft in|1.90}} tall<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.9"/><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 81.</ref> with blue eyes and blond hair,<ref name="Schwarcz, p.68"/><ref name="Barman 1999, p.97"/><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.9">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 9.</ref> was described as handsome.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.50"/><ref name="Barman 1999, p.97"/><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 187.</ref> With growth, his weaknesses faded and his strengths of character came to the fore. He learned to be not only impartial and diligent, but also courteous, patient and personable. As he began to fully exercise authority, his new social skills and diligence in government contributed greatly to his effectiveness and public image.<ref name="Barman1999, p.109"/> Historian Roderick J. Barman describes him at this time: "He kept his emotions under iron discipline. He was never rude and never lost his temper. He was exceptionally discreet in words and cautious in action."<ref name="Barman1999, p.122">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 122.</ref>

The end of 1845 through the beginning of 1846 found the Emperor making a tour of Brazil's southern provinces, traveling through [[Santa Catarina (state)|Santa Catarina]], [[S<U+00E3>o Paulo]] (of which [[Paran<U+00E1> (state)|Paran<U+00E1>]] was a part at this time) and [[Rio Grande do Sul]]. He was buoyed by the warm and enthusiastic responses he received.<ref name="Barman1999 p.111">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 111.</ref> This success encouraged him, for the first time in his life, to act confidently on his own initiative and insights.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 111<U+2013>112.</ref> Most importantly, this period saw the end of the Courtier Faction. Pedro II successfully engineered the end of the courtiers' influence by removing them from his inner circle while avoiding any public disruption.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 114.</ref>
[[File:Pedro II 1850 Brazil.JPG|thumb|200px|right|alt=A head and shoulders daguerreotype portrait of a young man with short beard wearing a dark suit and cravat|Pedro II, c.&nbsp;1848 (age 22): earliest surviving photograph of the Emperor]]
Pedro II was faced by three crises between 1848 and 1852.<ref name="Barman1999, p.122"/> The first test came in confronting the trade in illegally imported slaves. This had been banned in 1826 as part of a treaty with Britain.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 123.</ref> Trafficking continued unabated, however, and the British government's passage of the [[Aberdeen Act]] of 1845 authorized British warships to board Brazilian shipping and seize any found involved in the slave trade.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 122<U+2013>123.</ref> While Brazil grappled with this problem, the [[Praieira revolt]] erupted on 6 November 1848. This was a conflict between local political factions within [[Pernambuco]] province, and was suppressed by March 1849. A bill was [[Promulgation|promulgated]] on 4 September 1850 which gave government broad authority to combat the illegal slave trade. With this new tool, Brazil moved to eliminate importation of slaves. By 1852 this first crisis was over, with Britain accepting that the trade had been suppressed.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 124.</ref>

The third crisis entailed a conflict with the [[Argentine Confederation]] regarding ascendancy over territories adjacent to the [[R<U+00ED>o de la Plata]] and free navigation of that waterway.<ref name="Barman1999 p.125">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 125.</ref> Since the 1830s, Argentine dictator Don [[Juan Manuel de Rosas]] had supported rebellions within [[Uruguay]] and Brazil. It was only in 1850 that Brazil was able to address the threat posed by Rosas.<ref name="Barman1999 p.125"/> An alliance was forged between Brazil, Uruguay and disaffected Argentines,<ref name="Barman1999 p.125"/> leading to the [[Platine War]] and the subsequent overthrow of the Argentine ruler in February 1852.<ref name="Barman1999, p.126">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 126.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 102<U+2013>103.</ref> In the words of historian Roderick J. Barman, a "considerable portion of the credit must be [...] assigned to the emperor, whose cool head, tenacity of purpose, and sense of what was feasible proved indispensable."<ref name="Barman1999, p.122"/>

The Empire's successful navigation of these crises considerably enhanced the nation's stability and prestige, and Brazil emerged as a hemispheric power.<ref>[[#refLevine1999|Levine (1999)]], pp. 63<U+2013>64.</ref> Internationally, Europeans began to regard the country as embodying familiar liberal ideals, such as freedom of the press and constitutional respect for civil liberties. Its representative parliamentary monarchy also stood in stark contrast to the mix of dictatorships and instability endemic in the other nations of South America during this period.{{ref label|specialnote_B|B|none}}<ref name="Skidmore 2003 p. 73">[[#refSkidmore2003|Skidmore (2003)]], p. 73.</ref><ref>[[#refBethell1993|Bethell (1993)]], p. 76.</ref><ref>[[#refGraham1994|Graham (1994)]], p. 71.</ref>

==Growth==
{{Main|Growth of Pedro II of Brazil}}

===Pedro II and politics===
[[File:Pedro II of Brazil 1853.jpg|thumb|220px|left|alt=Photographic half-length portrait of a seated bearded man dressed in a dark, double-breasted coat with his right hand tucked inside the front|Pedro II, around age 25, c.&nbsp;1851]]
At the beginning of the 1850s, Brazil was enjoying internal stability and economic prosperity.<ref name="Barman1999 p.159">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 159.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 100.</ref> The nation was being interconnected through [[railroad]], electric [[telegraph]] and [[steamship]] lines, uniting it into a single entity.<ref name="Barman1999 p.159"/> The general opinion, both at home and abroad, was that these accomplishments had been possible for two reasons: "its governance as a [[monarchy]] and the character of Pedro II".<ref name="Barman1999 p.159"/>

Pedro II was neither a British-style [[figurehead]] nor an autocrat in the manner of [[List of Russian rulers|Russian czars]]. The Emperor exercised power through cooperation with elected politicians, economic interests, and popular support.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 161<U+2013>162.</ref> This interdependence and interaction did much to influence the direction of Pedro II's reign.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 162.</ref> The Emperor's more notable political successes were achieved due largely to the non-confrontational and cooperative manner with which he approached both issues and the partisan figures with whom he had to deal. He was remarkably tolerant, seldom taking offense at criticism, opposition, or even incompetence.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 164.</ref> He was diligent in appointing only highly-qualified candidates to positions in the government, and sought to curb corruption.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 163.</ref> He did not have the constitutional authority to force acceptance of his initiatives without support, and his collaborative approach towards governing kept the nation progressing and enabled the political system to successfully function.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 165.</ref>

The uncertainty of his childhood and exploitation at the hands of others during his youth made the Emperor determined to maintain control over his own destiny. Achieving self-determination required that sufficient power be acquired and maintained.<ref name="Barman1999 p.167">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 167.</ref> He used his active and essential participation in directing the course of government as a means of influence. His direction became indispensable, although it never devolved into "one-man rule."<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 178.</ref> The Emperor respected the prerogatives of the legislature, even when they resisted, delayed, or thwarted his goals and appointments.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 178<U+2013>179.</ref>

The Brazilian national political system resembled those in other [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] nations. The Emperor, as [[head of state]], would ask the leader of either the [[Conservative Party (Brazil)|Conservative]] or Liberal Party to form a cabinet. The other party formed the opposition in the legislature, a counterweight and check on the party in power. If support for the party in power diminished greatly, or if the cabinet resigned, the Emperor could call on others from either party to form a new government. "In his handling of the two parties, he needed to maintain a reputation for impartiality, work in accord with the popular mood, and avoid any flagrant imposition of his will on the political scene."<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 120.</ref> 

The active presence of Pedro II on the political scene was an important part of the government's structure, which also included the cabinet, the [[Chamber of Deputies of Brazil|Chamber of Deputies]] and the [[Senate of Brazil|Senate]] (the latter two formed the National Assembly, or Parliament). Most politicians appreciated and supported the Emperor's role. Many had lived through the regency period, when the lack of an emperor who could stand above petty and special interests led to years of strife between political factions. Their experiences in public life had created a conviction that the Emperor was "indispensable to Brazil's continued peace and prosperity."<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 170.</ref>

===Domestic life===
[[File:Princess Isabel and Leopoldina 1855.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=An oval, framed photographic portrait of two young girls dressed in elaborate Victorian-era gowns|Pedro II's surviving children in 1855: Princesses [[Princess Leopoldina of Brazil|Leopoldina]] and [[Isabel, Princess Imperial of Brazil|Isabel]] (seated)]]
The marriage between Pedro II and Teresa Cristina started off badly. With maturity, patience, and their first child, [[Afonso, Prince Imperial of Brazil|Afonso]], their relationship improved.<ref name="Barman1999, p.126"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 73.</ref> Later Teresa gave birth to more children: [[Isabel, Princess Imperial of Brazil|Isabel]], in 1846; [[Princess Leopoldina of Brazil|Leopoldina]], in 1847; and lastly, Pedro, in 1848.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.52"/><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 127.</ref><ref name="Vainfas2002 p.200">[[#refVainfas2002|Vainfas (2002)]], p. 200.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 98.</ref> However, both boys died when very young, which devastated the Emperor.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.52"/><ref name="Vainfas2002 p.200"/><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 129.</ref> Beyond suffering as a father, his view of the Empire's future changed completely. Despite his affection for his daughters, he did not believe that Princess Isabel, although his heir, would have any chance of prospering on the throne. He felt his successor needed to be male for the monarchy to be viable.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 129<U+2013>130.</ref> He increasingly saw the Imperial system as being tied so inextricably to himself, that it would not survive him.<ref name="Barman1999 p.130">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 130.</ref> Isabel and her sister received exceptional educations,<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 151.</ref> although they were given no preparation for governing the nation. Pedro II excluded Isabel from participation in government business and decisions.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 152.</ref>

Sometime around 1850, Pedro II began having discreet affairs with other women.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 128.</ref> The most famous and enduring of these relationships involved [[Lu<U+00ED>sa de Barros, Countess of Barral|Lu<U+00ED>sa Margarida Portugal de Barros, Countess of Barral]], with whom he formed a romantic and intimate, though not adulterous, friendship after she was appointed governess to the emperor's daughters in November 1856.<ref name="Vainfas2002 p.200"/><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 147<U+2013>148.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 65.</ref> Throughout his life, the Emperor held onto a hope of finding a soulmate, something he felt cheated of<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 148.</ref> due to the necessity of a [[marriage of state]] to a woman for whom he never felt passion.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 144.</ref> This is but one instance illustrating the Emperor's dual identity: who on one hand was "Dom Pedro II" who assiduously carried out his duty in the role of Emperor which destiny had assigned to him, and who on the other hand was "Pedro de Alc<U+00E2>ntara" who considered the Imperial office an unrewarding burden and who was happier in the worlds of literature and science.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.80">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 80.</ref> Pedro II was what would today be termed a [[workaholic]], and his routine was demanding. He usually woke up at 7&nbsp;am and did not sleep before 2 in the morning. His entire day was devoted to the affairs of state and the meager free time available was spent reading and studying.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 134.</ref> The Emperor went about his daily routine dressed in a simple black tail coat, trousers, and cravat. For special occasions he would wear court dress, and he only appeared in full regalia with crown, mantle and scepter twice each year at the opening and closing of the National Assembly.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 133<U+2013>134.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], pp. 54<U+2013>55.</ref> 

Pedro II held politicians and government officials to the strict standards which he exemplified.<ref name="Skidmore 2003 p. 73"/> The Emperor demanded politicians work at least an eight hour day and adopted a strict policy for the selection of civil servants based on morality and merit.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 83.</ref> To set the standard, he lived simply. [[Ballroom dance|Balls]] and assemblies of the Court ceased after 1852.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.80"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 53.</ref> He also refused to request or allow the amount of his [[civil list]] (Rs 800:000$000 per year, about then-U.S. $405,000 or <U+00A3>90,000<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 439.</ref>) to be raised from 1840, when it represented 3% of the government expenditures, until 1889, when it had fallen to 0.5%.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 97.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 51.</ref> He refused luxury,<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 93.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 47.</ref><ref>[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 38.</ref> once explaining: "I believe that useless expenditure is robbing the Nation."<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.79">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 79.</ref>

===Patron of arts and sciences===
[[File:Pedro II 1858.jpg|thumb|210px|left|alt=Photograph of a man with a full beard and dressed in a dark frock coat who is seated at a table holding a book with bookshelves in the background|Pedro II c.&nbsp;1858. In the 1850s, books begin to feature prominently in his portraits, a reference to his role as advocate for education.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 326.</ref>]]
"I was born to devote myself to culture and sciences", the Emperor remarked in his private journal during 1862.<ref name="Lyrav.2 p.104">[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 104.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 77.</ref> He had always been eager to learn and found in books a refuge from the demands of his position.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 116.</ref><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 59.</ref> His ability to recall passages which he had read in the past was notable.<ref name="Barman1999, p.117">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 117.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 223.</ref> Subjects which interested Pedro II were wide-ranging, including [[anthropology]], [[history]], [[geography]], [[geology]], [[medicine]], [[law]], [[religious studies]], [[philosophy]], [[painting]], [[sculpture]], [[theater]], [[music]], [[chemistry]], [[physics]], [[astronomy]], [[poetry]], [[technology]], among others.<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 99.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 542.</ref> By the end of his reign, there were three libraries in S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o palace containing more than 60,000 volumes.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 227.</ref> A passion for [[linguistics]] prompted him throughout his life to study new languages, and he was able to speak and write not only [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] but also [[Latin]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[English language|English]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Sanskrit]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Occitan language|Occitan]] and [[Tupi-Guarani languages|Tupi-Guarani]].<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 226.</ref><ref>[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 7.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 428.</ref><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 401.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 103.</ref> He became the first Brazilian photographer when he acquired a [[daguerreotype]] camera in March 1840.<ref>[[#refVasquez2003|Vasquez (2003)]], p. 77.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 345.</ref> He set up one laboratory in S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o devoted to photography and another to chemistry and physics. He also had an astronomical observatory constructed.<ref name="Barman1999, p.117"/>

The Emperor's erudition amazed [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] when both met.<ref name="Vainfas2002 p.200"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 230.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1389.</ref> [[Victor Hugo]] told him: "Sire, you are a great citizen, you are the grandson of [[Marcus Aurelius]]",<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 258.</ref><ref name="Carvalho2007 p.172">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 172.</ref> and [[Alexandre Herculano]] called him: "A Prince whom the general opinion holds as the foremost of his era because of his gifted mind, and due to the constant application of that gift to the sciences and culture."<ref name="Lyrav.2 p.104"/> He became a member of the [[Royal Society]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 194.</ref> the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]],<ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1787">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1787.</ref> [[The Royal Academies for Science and the Arts of Belgium]]<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 94.</ref> and the [[American Geographical Society]].<ref name="Barman1999, p.280">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 280.</ref> In 1875, he was elected to the [[French Academy of Sciences]], an honor previously granted to only two other heads of state: [[Peter I of Russia|Peter the Great]] and [[Napoleon I|Napoleon Bonaparte]].<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.172"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 255.</ref> Pedro II exchanged letters with scientists, philosophers, musicians and other intellectuals. Many of his correspondents became his friends, including [[Richard Wagner]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 185.</ref> [[Louis Pasteur]],<ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 49.</ref> [[Louis Agassiz]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 193.</ref> [[John Greenleaf Whittier]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 238.</ref> [[Michel Eug<U+00E8>ne Chevreul]],<ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 57.</ref> [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 236.</ref> [[Arthur de Gobineau]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 195.</ref> [[Fr<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ric Mistral]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 196.</ref> [[Alessandro Manzoni]],<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 187.</ref> Alexandre Herculano,<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 179.</ref> [[Camilo Castelo Branco]]<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 200.</ref> and [[James Cooley Fletcher]].<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 201.</ref>

Pedro II early realized that he had an opportunity to put the knowledge he was accumulating to practical use for Brazil's benefit.<ref name="Barman1999, p.118">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 118.</ref> The Emperor considered education to be of national importance and was himself a concrete example of the value of learning.<ref name="Barman1999, p.118"/><ref name="Barman1999, p.119">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 119.</ref> He remarked: "Were I not an Emperor, I would like to be a teacher. I do not know of a task more noble than to direct young minds and prepare the men of tomorrow."<ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], pp. 94<U+2013>95.</ref> Education also helped toward his goal to create a sense of Brazilian [[nationhood|national]] identity.<ref name="Schwarcz1998 p.126">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 126.</ref> His reign saw the creation of the [[Brazilian Historic and Geographic Institute]] to promote research and preservation in the historical, geographical, cultural and social sciences.<ref name="Schwarcz1998 p.126"/> The  Imperial Academy of Music and National Opera<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 152</ref> and the [[Col<U+00E9>gio Pedro II (Rio de Janeiro)|Pedro II School]] were also founded, the latter serving as a model for schools throughout Brazil.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], pp. 150<U+2013>151.</ref> The [[Escola Nacional de Belas Artes|Imperial Academy of the Fine Arts]], established by his father, received further strengthening and support.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 144.</ref> Using his civil list income, Pedro II provided scholarships for Brazilian students to study at universities, art schools and conservatories of music in Europe.<ref name="Barman1999, p.119"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 99.</ref> He also financed the creation of the [[Institute Pasteur]], helped underwrite the construction of Wagner's [[Bayreuth Festspielhaus]], as well as subscribing to similar projects.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 226<U+2013>228.</ref> His efforts were recognized both at home and abroad. [[Charles Darwin]] said of him: "The Emperor does so much for science, that every scientific man is bound to show him the utmost respect".<ref name="Vainfas2002 p.200"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 182.</ref>

===Popularity and clash with the British Empire===
[[File:Familia imperial 1861.jpg|thumb|250px|right|alt=Photograph showing a group of men and women standing at the foot of stairs leading up to a white house with dark shutters|Pedro II at age 35 along with his wife and daughters visiting a farm in southern [[Minas Gerais]] province, 1861]]
At the end of 1859, Pedro II departed on a trip to provinces north of the capital, visiting [[Esp<U+00ED>rito Santo]], [[Bahia]], [[Sergipe]], [[Alagoas]], [[Pernambuco]] and [[Para<U+00ED>ba]]. He returned in February 1860 after four months. The trip was a huge success, with the Emperor welcomed everywhere with warmth and joy.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], pp. 200<U+2013>207.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 138<U+2013>141.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 188.</ref>

The first half of the 1860s saw peace and prosperity in Brazil. [[Civil liberty|Civil liberties]] were maintained.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 200.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 192.</ref> [[Freedom of speech]] had existed since Brazil's independence<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 515.</ref> and continued to be strongly defended by Pedro II.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 84.</ref><ref name="Besouchet, p.508">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 508.</ref> The Emperor found newspapers from the capital and from the provinces an ideal way to keep track of public opinion and the nation's overall situation.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.79"/> Another means of monitoring the Empire was through direct contacts with his subjects. One opportunity for this was during regular Tuesday and Saturday public audiences, where anyone of any social class (including slaves<ref name="Olivieri1999 p.27">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 27.</ref>) could gain admittance and present their petitions and stories.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 180.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 94.</ref> Visits to schools, colleges, prisons, exhibitions, factories, barracks, and other public appearances presented further opportunities to gather first-hand information.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 184.</ref> 

This tranquility disappeared when the British consul in Rio de Janeiro, William Dougal Christie, nearly sparked a war between his nation and Brazil. Christie, who believed in [[Gunboat diplomacy]],<ref name="Calmon1975 p.678">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 678.</ref> sent an [[ultimatum]] containing abusive demands arising out of two minor incidents at the end of 1861 and beginning of 1862. The first was the sinking of a commercial [[barque]] on the coast of Rio Grande do Sul after which its goods were pillaged by local inhabitants. The second was the arrest of drunken British officers who were causing a disturbance in the streets of Rio.<ref name="Calmon1975 p.678"/><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 207.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 103<U+2013>145.</ref> The Brazilian government refused to yield, and Christie issued orders for British warships to capture Brazilian merchant vessels as indemnity.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 208.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], pp. 678<U+2013>681.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 104.</ref> Brazil's Navy prepared for imminent conflict,<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 680.</ref> purchase of coastal artillery was ordered,<ref>[[#refDoratioto2002|Doratioto (2002)]], p. 98.</ref> several [[ironclad]]s were authorized<ref>[[#refDoratioto2002|Doratioto (2002)]], p. 203.</ref> and coastal defenses were given permission to fire upon any British warship that tried to capture Brazilian merchant ships.<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 684.</ref> Pedro II was the main reason for Brazil's resistance, he rejected any suggestion of yielding.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 104<U+2013>105.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 191.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 209.</ref> This response came as a surprise to Christie, who changed his tenor and proposed a peaceful settlement through international arbitration.<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 685.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 210.</ref><ref name="Carvalho2007 p.105">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 105.</ref> The Brazilian government presented its demands and, upon seeing the British government's position weaken, severed diplomatic ties with Britain in June 1863.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.105"/><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 691.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 211.</ref>

== War of the Triple Alliance==
{{Main|Pedro II of Brazil in the War of the Triple Alliance}}
{{See also|Uruguayan War|War of the Triple Alliance}}

===First Fatherland Volunteer===
[[Image:Pedro II 1865 01.jpg|thumb|left|200px|alt=Photograph of a seated, bearded man dressed in a dark suit and vest|Pedro II at age 39, 1865]]
As war with the British Empire threatened, Brazil had to turn its attention to its southern frontiers. Another civil war had begun in [[Uruguay]] turning its political parties against each other.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.108">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 108.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 219.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 197.</ref> The internal conflict led to the murder of Brazilians and looting of their property in Uruguay.<ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 220.</ref> Brazil's government decided to intervene, fearful of giving any impression of weakness in the face of conflict with the British.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.107">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 107.</ref> A Brazilian army invaded Uruguay in December 1864 beginning the brief [[Uruguayan War]], which ended on 20 February 1865.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.109">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 109.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], pp. 224<U+2013>225.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 198.</ref>

Meanwhile, in December 1864 the dictator of Paraguay, [[Francisco Solano L<U+00F3>pez (politician)|Francisco Solano L<U+00F3>pez]] took advantage of the situation to establish his country as a regional power. The [[Paraguayan army]] invaded the Brazilian province of [[Mato Grosso]] (currently the state of [[Mato Grosso do Sul]]), triggering the [[War of the Triple Alliance]]. Four months later, Paraguayan troops invaded [[Argentina|Argentine]] territory as a prelude to an attack upon the Brazilian province of [[Rio Grande do Sul]].<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.109"/><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 299.</ref><ref name="Lyra v.1, p.227">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 227.</ref> 

Aware of the anarchy in Rio Grande do Sul and the incapacity and incompetence of its military chiefs to resist the Paraguayan army, Pedro II decided to go to the front in person.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.228">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 228.</ref> Both the Cabinet and the National Assembly refused to accede to the Emperor's wish.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.228"/><ref name="Calmon 1975, p.734">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 734.</ref> After he also received objections from the [[Privy council|Council of State]], Pedro II made the memorable pronouncement: "If they can prevent me from going as an Emperor, they cannot prevent me from abdicating and going as a Fatherland Volunteer".<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.228"/><ref name="Calmon 1975, p.734"/><ref>[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 32.</ref><ref name="Barman1999, p.202">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 202.</ref> Thus those Brazilians who volunteered to go to war became known throughout the nation as the "Fatherland Volunteers" in homage to Pedro II's quote.<ref name="Calmon 1975, p.734"/> The monarch himself was popularly called the "Number-one volunteer."<ref name="Vainfas2002 p.200"/><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 300.</ref>

Pedro II left for the south in July 1865.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.229">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 229.</ref><ref name="Calmon 1975, p.735">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 735.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 111.</ref> He disembarked in Rio Grande do Sul a few days later and proceeded from there by land.<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 736.</ref> The overland journey was made by horse and wagon, and at night the emperor slept in a campaign tent.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.112">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 112.</ref> Pedro II arrived in [[Uruguaiana]], a Brazilian town occupied by the Paraguayan army, on 11 September.<ref name="Salles 2003, p.52">[[#refSalles2003|Salles (2003)]], p. 52.</ref> By the time of the Emperor's arrival, the Paraguayan force was besieged.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.114">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 114.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 745.</ref>
[[Image:Pedro II Admiral Brazil 1870.jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=Photograph of a bearded man seated casually with crossed legs and wearing a military tunic with fringed epaulettes|Dressed in an admiral's uniform at age 44, 1870<U+2014>the war years had prematurely aged the Emperor<ref name="Lyra v.2, p.161">[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 161.</ref>]]
The Emperor rode within rifle-shot of Uruguaiana to demonstrate his courage, but the Paraguayans did not attack him.<ref name="Calmon 1975, p.744">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 744.</ref><ref>[[#refPedrosa2004|Pedrosa (2004)]], p. 199.</ref> To avoid further bloodshed, he offered terms of surrender to the Paraguayan commander, which was accepted.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.114"/><ref name="Calmon 1975, p.748">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 748.</ref><ref name="Lyra v.1, p.237">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 237.</ref> Pedro II's coordination of the military operations and his personal example played a decisive role in successfully repulsing the Paraguayan invasion of Brazilian territory.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 205.</ref> There was a general belief that the war was near its end and that the surrender of L<U+00F3>pez was imminent.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.114"/><ref>[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 239.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 725.</ref> Before leaving Uruguaiana, he received the British ambassador [[Edward Thornton (diplomat)|Edward Thornton]], who publicly apologized on behalf of Queen Victoria and the British Government for the crisis between the empires.<ref name="Calmon 1975, p.748"/><ref name="Lyra v.1, p.237"/> The emperor considered that this diplomatic victory over the most powerful nation of the world was sufficient and renewed friendly relations between the nations.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.237"/> He returned to [[Rio de Janeiro]] and was received with huge celebrations.<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 750.</ref>

===Conclusion of hostilities===
Against all expectations, the war continued for almost five years. During this period, Pedro II's time and energy were devoted to prosecuting the war effort.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 193.</ref><ref name="Carvalho2007 p.110">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 110.</ref> He tirelessly worked to raise and equip troops to reinforce the front lines, and to push forward the fitting of new warships for the navy.<ref name="Barman1999, p.202"/> At the same time, he worked to prevent quarrels between the national political parties from impairing the military response.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 219<U+2013>224.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 116<U+2013>118.</ref> His refusal to accept any outcome short of total victory over the enemy was pivotal in the final outcome.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 206.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 114<U+2013>115.</ref> His tenacity was well-paid with the news that L<U+00F3>pez had died in battle on 1 March 1870, bringing the war to a close.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 229<U+2013>230.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 121.</ref>

More than 50,000 Brazilian soldiers had died,<ref>[[#refDoratioto2002|Doratioto (2002)]], p. 461.</ref> and war costs equalled eleven times the government's annual budget.<ref>[[#refDoratioto2002|Doratioto (2002)]], p. 462.</ref> However, the country was so prosperous, that the government was able to retire the war debt in only ten years.<ref>[[#refCalmon2002|Calmon (2002)]], p. 201.</ref><ref>[[#refMunro1942|Munro (1942)]], p. 277.</ref> The conflict was a stimulus to national production and economic growth.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 243.</ref> Pedro II turned down the National Assembly's suggestion to erect an [[equestrian statue]] of him to commemorate the victory and chose instead to use the money to build elementary schools.<ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 855.</ref><ref>[[#refDoratioto2002|Doratioto (2002)]], p. 455.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 122.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 230.</ref>

==Apogee==
{{Main|Apogee of Pedro II of Brazil}}

===Abolitionist on the throne===
[[Image:Fala do trono.jpg|thumb|left|200px|alt=Full length painted portrait of a bearded man wearing a gold crown, mantle and sword and grasping a long scepter|Emperor Dom Pedro II at age 46 delivering the [[Speech from the Throne]] wearing the [[Imperial Regalia of Brazil|Imperial Regalia]], 1872]]
The diplomatic victory over the British Empire and the military victory over Uruguay in 1865, followed by a successful conclusion of the war with Paraguay in 1870, ushered in what is considered the "[[golden age]]" and apogee of the Brazilian Empire.<ref name="Lyra v.2, p.9">[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 9.</ref> The 1870s were good times in Brazil, and the Emperor's popularity was greater than ever. Progress was made in both social and political spheres, and all segments of society benefited from the reforms and shared in the increasing prosperity.<ref>[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 37.</ref> Brazil's international reputation for political stability and investment potential greatly improved. The Empire was seen as a modern and progressive nation unequalled, with the exception of the [[United States]], in the [[Americas]].<ref name="Lyra v.2, p.9"/> The economy began undergoing rapid growth, and immigration flourished. Railroad, shipping and other modernization projects were adopted. "With slavery destined for extinction and other reforms projected, the prospects for 'moral and material advances' seemed vast."<ref name="Barman1999, p.240">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 240.</ref>

In 1870, few Brazilians opposed slavery and even fewer took an open stand against it. Pedro II was one of the few who did oppose slavery,<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.189">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 189.</ref><ref name="Barman1999, p.194">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 194.</ref> which he considered "a national shame."<ref name="Olivieri, p.44">[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 44.</ref> The Emperor never owned slaves.<ref name="Barman1999, p.194"/> In 1823, slaves formed 29 percent of Brazil's population, but this figure had fallen to 15.2 percent by 1872.<ref>[[#refVainfas2002|Vainfas (2002)]], p. 239.</ref> The abolition of slavery was a delicate subject in Brazil. Slaves were used by everyone, from the richest to the poorest.<ref>[[#refOlivieri1999|Olivieri (1999)]], p. 43.</ref><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.130">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 130.</ref> Pedro II wanted to end slavery gradually<ref name="Lyra v.2, p.161"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 131.</ref> to soften the impact to the national economy.<ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 29.</ref> He consciously ignored the growing political damage to his image and to the monarchy in consequence of his support for abolition.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 224<U+2013>225.</ref>

The Emperor had no constitutional authority to directly intervene to put an end to slavery.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 210.</ref> He would need to use all his skills to convince, influence and gather support among politicians to achieve his goal.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 132<U+2013>136.</ref> His first open move against slavery<ref name="Olivieri, p.44"/> occurred in 1850, when he threatened to abdicate unless the National Assembly declared the [[Atlantic slave trade]] illegal.<ref name="Lyra v.1, p.166">[[#refLyrav1|Lyra (v.1, 1977)]], p. 166.</ref>

After the overseas source for supplying new slaves had been eliminated, Pedro II turned his attention in the early 1860s to removing the remaining source: enslavement of children born to slaves.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.132">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 132.</ref><ref name="Lyra v.2, p.162">[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 162.</ref> Legislation was drafted at his initiative,<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.132"/> but the conflict with Paraguay delayed discussion of the proposal in the National Assembly.<ref name="Lyra v.2, p.162"/><ref name="Schwarcz, p.315">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 315.</ref> Pedro II openly asked for the gradual eradication of slavery in the [[Speech from the Throne]] of 1867.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 134.</ref> He was heavily criticized, and his move was condemned as "national suicide."<ref name="Schwarcz, p.315"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 133.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 164.</ref> The charge was aired "that abolition was his personal desire and not that of the nation."<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.136">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 136.</ref> Eventually, the bill was enacted as the "Law of Free Birth" on 28 September 1871, under which all children born to slave women after that date were considered free-born.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.136"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 170.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 238.</ref>

===To Europe and North Africa===
[[Image:Pedro II of Brazil in Egypt 1871.jpg|thumb|right|300px|alt=A large group of men and women are gathered below the head of the Sphinx with the Great Pyramid looming behind|[[Auguste Mariette]] (seated, far left) and Pedro II (seated, far right) with others during the Emperor's visit to the [[Giza Necropolis]] at the end of 1871]]
On 25 May 1871 Pedro II and his wife traveled to Europe.<ref name="Barman1999 p.236">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 236.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 175.</ref> He had long desired to vacation abroad. When news arrived that his younger daughter, the 23-year-old Lepoldina, had died in Vienna of [[typhoid fever]] on 7 February, he finally had a pressing reason to venture outside the Empire.<ref name="Barman1999 p.236"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], pp. 172, 174.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 144<U+2013>145.</ref> Upon arriving in [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]], he immediately went to the [[National Museum of Ancient Art|''Janelas Verdes'' palace]], where he met with his stepmother [[Am<U+00E9>lie of Leuchtenberg]]. The two had not seen each other in forty years, and the meeting was emotional. Pedro II remarked in his journal: "I cried from happiness and also from sorrow seeing my Mother so affectionate toward me but so aged and so sick."<ref name="Barman1999 p.236"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 180.</ref><ref name="Carvalho2007 p.147">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 147.</ref> 

The Emperor proceeded to visit Spain, Great Britain, Belgium, Germany, Austria, Italy, Egypt, Greece, Switzerland and France. In [[Coburg]] he visited his daughter's tomb.<ref name="Carvalho2007 p.147"/><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 237<U+2013>238.</ref> He found this to be "a time of release and freedom". He traveled under the assumed name "Dom Pedro de Alc<U+00E2>ntara", insisting upon being treated informally and staying only in hotels.<ref name="Barman1999 p.236"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 146<U+2013>147.</ref> He spent his days sightseeing and conversing with scientists and other intellectuals with whom he shared interests.<ref name="Barman1999 p.236"/><ref name="Carvalho2007 p.147"/> The European sojourn proved to be a success, and his demeanor and curiosity won respectful notices in the nations which he visited. The prestige of both Brazil and Pedro II were further enhanced during the tour when news came from Brazil that the Law of Free Birth, abolishing the last source of enslavement, had been ratified. The Imperial party returned to Brazil in triumph on 31 March 1872.<ref name="Barman1999, p.240"/>

===Quarrel with bishops===
[[Image:Delfim-pedroII-MHN.jpg|thumb|left|210px|alt=Painted portrait of bearded man in formal dress seated in an armchair with his left hand turning a page of an open book|Pedro II at age 49, 1875]]
Soon after returning to Brazil, Pedro II was faced with an unexpected crisis. The clergy had long been understaffed, undisciplined and poorly educated,<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258.">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 254.</ref><ref name="Carvalho2007, p.151">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 151.</ref> leading to a great loss of respect for the Catholic Church.<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258."/> The Imperial government had embarked upon a program of reform to address these deficiencies.<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258."/> As the Catholic Church was the state religion, the Emperor exercised a great deal of control over Church affairs,<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258."/> paying clerical salaries, appointing parish priests, nominating bishops, ratifying papal bulls, and overseeing seminaries.<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258."/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 150.</ref> In pursuing reform, the government selected bishops which satisfied its criteria for education, support for reform and moral fitness.<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258."/><ref name="Carvalho2007, p.151"/> However, as more capable men began to fill the clerical ranks, resentment of government control over the Church increased.<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258."/><ref name="Carvalho2007, p.151"/>

The bishops of [[Olinda]] and [[Par<U+00E1>]] were two of the new generation of educated, zealous Brazilian clerics. They had been influenced by the [[Ultramontanism]] which spread in Catholicism in this period. In 1872 they ordered [[Freemasonry|Freemasons]] expelled from [[lay brother]]hoods.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 255<U+2013>256.</ref><ref name="Carvalho2007, p.153">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 153.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], pp. 205<U+2013>206.</ref> Although European Masonry often tended towards [[atheism]] and [[anti-clericalism]], things were much different in Brazil<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 255.</ref> where membership in Masonic orders was common.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 256.</ref> The government tried on two separate occasions to persuade the bishops to repeal, but they refused. This led to them being tried before the [[Superior Court of Justice (Brazil)|Superior Court of Justice]] and convicted. In 1874, they were sentenced four years at hard labor, although the Emperor commuted this to imprisonment only.<ref name="Barman1999, p.257">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 257.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 152.</ref><ref name="Lyrav21977 p.208">[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 208.</ref> Pedro II played a decisive role by unequivocally backing the government's actions.<ref name="Barman1999, pp. 257<U+2013>258."/><ref name="Carvalho2007, p.153"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 212.</ref>

Pedro II was a conscientious adherent of Catholicism, which he viewed as advancing important civilizing and civic values. While meticulously orthodox in matters of doctrine, he felt free to think and behave independently.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 253.</ref> The Emperor accepted new ideas, such as [[Charles Darwin]]'s Theory of [[Evolution]], of which he remarked that "the laws that he [Darwin] has discovered glorify the [[God in Christianity|Creator]]".<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 34.</ref> He was moderate in his religious beliefs,<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 92.</ref> but could not accept disrespect to civil law and government authority.<ref name="Carvalho2007, p.153"/><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 213.</ref> As he told his son-in-law: "[The government] has to ensure that the constitution is obeyed. In these proceedings there is no desire to protect masonry; but rather the goal of upholding the rights of the civilian power."<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 157.</ref> The crisis was resolved in September 1875 after the Emperor agreed to grant full amnesty to the bishops and annul their expulsion orders.<ref name="Lyrav21977 p.208"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 156.</ref> The main consequence of the crisis was that the clergy no longer saw any benefit in upholding Pedro II's throne.<ref name="Carvalho2007, p.153"/> Although they abandoned the Emperor, most eagerly awaited the accession of his eldest daughter and heir Isabel because of her [[Ultramontanism|ultramontane]] views.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 155.</ref>

===To the U.S., Europe and Mideast===
[[Image:Pedro II of Brazil Niagara Falls 1876.png|thumb|right|250px|alt=Photograph of three people, two women and a bearded man, seated on a park bench with six other men standing in back and waterfalls in the distance|Pedro II (seated, right) at [[Niagara Falls]], 1876]]
Once again the Emperor traveled abroad, this time going to the [[United States]]. He was accompanied by his faithful servant Rafael, who had raised him from childhood.<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 275.</ref> Pedro II arrived in New York City on 15 April 1876, and set out from there to travel throughout the country; going as far as [[San Francisco]] in the west, [[New Orleans]] in the south, [[Washington, D.C.]], and north to [[Toronto]], [[Canada]].<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 277<U+2013>279.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 161<U+2013>170.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], pp. 227<U+2013>240.</ref> The trip was "an unnalloyed triumph", Pedro II making a deep impression on the American people with his simplicity and kindness.<ref name="Barman1999, p.280"/><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 169.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 241.</ref> He then crossed the Atlantic, where he visited [[Denmark]], [[Sweden]], [[Finland]], [[Russia]], [[Turkey]], Greece, the [[Holy Land#Christianity|Holy Land]], Egypt, Italy, Austria, Germany, France, Britain, [[Netherlands]], [[Switzerland]] and Portugal.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 280<U+2013>282.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav2|Lyra (v.2, 1977)]], p. 222.</ref> He returned to Brazil on 22 September 1877.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 286.</ref>

Pedro II's trips abroad made a deep psychological impact. While traveling, he was largely freed of the restrictions imposed by his office.<ref name="Barman1999, p.245">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 245.</ref> Under the pseudonym "Pedro de Alc<U+00E2>ntara", he enjoyed moving about as an ordinary person, even taking a train journey alone with his wife. Only while touring abroad could the Emperor shake off the formal existence and demands of the life he knew in Brazil.<ref name="Barman1999, p.245"/> It became more difficult to reacclimate to his routine as head of state upon returning.<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 248.</ref> Upon his sons' early deaths, the Emperor's faith in the monarchy's future had evaporated. His trips abroad now made him resentful of the burden destiny had placed upon his shoulders when only a child of five. If he previously had no interest in securing the throne for the next generation, he now had no desire to keep it going during his own lifetime.<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], pp. 248, 253.</ref>

==Decline and fall==
{{Main|Decline and fall of Pedro II of Brazil}}

===Decadence===
[[Image:Pedro II of Brazil Paris 1887.jpg|thumb|left|210px|alt=Photographic portrait of a man with a white beard seated in an armchair and holding a small book in his left hand while supporting his head with his right hand|Pedro II at age 61, 1887: an Emperor weary of his crown and resigned to the monarchy's demise]]
During the 1880s, Brazil continued to prosper and social diversity increased markedly, including the first organized push for [[women's rights]].<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 319.</ref> On the other hand, letters written by Pedro II reveal a man grown world-weary with age and having an increasingly alienated and pessimistic outlook.<ref name="Barman1999 p.298">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 298.</ref><ref name="Barman1999 p.299">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 299.</ref> He remained respectful of his duty and was meticulous in performing the tasks demanded of the Imperial office, albeit often without enthusiasm.<ref name="Barman1999 p.299"/> Because of his increasing "indifference towards the fate of the regime"<ref name="Lyra v.3, p.126">[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 126.</ref> and his lack of action in support of the Imperial system once it was challenged, historians have attributed the "prime, perhaps sole, responsibility" for the dissolution of the monarchy to the Emperor himself.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 399.</ref>

After their experience of the perils and obstacles of government, the political figures who had arisen during the 1830s looked to the Emperor as providing a fundamental source of authority essential both for governing and for national survival.<ref name="Barman1999, p.317"/> These elder statesmen began to die off or retire from government until, by the 1880s, they had almost entirely been replaced by a younger generation of politicians who had no experience of [[Early life of Pedro II of Brazil#The Regency|the Regency and early years]] of Pedro II's reign, when external and internal dangers threatened the nation's existence. They had only known a stable administration and prosperity.<ref name="Barman1999, p.317"/> In sharp contrast those of the previous era, the young politicians saw no reason to uphold and defend the Imperial office as a unifying force beneficial to the nation.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 318.</ref> Pedro II's role in achieving an era of national unity, stability and good government now went unremembered and unconsidered by the ruling elites. By his very success, the emperor had made his position seem unnecessary.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. xiv.</ref>

The lack of an heir who could feasibly provide a new direction for the nation also diminished the long-term prospects for continuation of the Brazilian monarchy. The Emperor loved his daughter Isabel, but he considered the idea of a female successor as antithetical to the role required of Brazil's ruler. He viewed the death of his two sons as being a sign that the Empire was destined to be supplanted.<ref name="Barman1999 p.262">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 262.</ref> Resistance to accepting a female ruler was also shared by the political establishment.<ref name="Barman1999 p.268">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 268.</ref> Even though the Constitution allowed female succession to the throne, Brazil was still very traditional, and only a male successor was thought capable as head of state.<ref name="Barman1999 p.130"/>

Republicanism was an elitist creed which never flourished in Brazil,<ref name="Barman1999 p.348">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 349.</ref><ref name="Lyra v.3, p.121">[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 121.</ref> with little support in the provinces.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.206">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 206.</ref><ref name="Munro, p.279">[[#refMunro1942|Munro (1942)]], p. 279.</ref><ref name="Ermakoff2006 p.189">[[#refErmakoff2006|Ermakoff (2006)]], p. 189.</ref> But a serious threat to the monarchy was the combination of republican ideas with the dissemination of [[Positivism]] among the army's lower and medium officer ranks, which led to indiscipline among the corps. They dreamed of a dictatorial republic which they believed would be superior to the liberal democractic monarchy.<ref name="Carvalho1990, p.41">[[#refCarvalho1990|Carvalho (1990)]], p. 41.</ref><ref name="Carvalho1990, p.41"/><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 498.</ref><ref name="Besouchet, p.33">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 33.</ref>

===Abolition and revolution===
[[Image:Fam<U+00ED>lia Imperial por Otto Hees.jpg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Photograph of a group of people assembled on a columned porch at the top of a flight of steps, with one older lady seated, one younger lady leaning on the arm of an older bearded man, two younger men and three small boys|The last picture of the Imperial Family in Brazil, 1889]]
The Emperor's health had considerably worsened<ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], pp. 53<U+2013>54.</ref> and his personal doctors suggested going to Europe for medical treatment.<ref name="Lyra v.3, p.56">[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 56.</ref> He left on 30 June 1887.<ref name="Lyra v.3, p.56"/> While in [[Milan]] he passed two weeks between life and death, even being anointed.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.199">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 199.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], pp. 61<U+2013>62.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1421.</ref> While on bed recovering, on 22 May he received news that [[Lei <U+00C1>urea|slavery had been abolished]] in Brazil.<ref name="Lyra v.3, p.62">[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 62.</ref> Lying in bed with a weak voice and tears in his eyes, he said, "Great people! Great people!"<ref name="Lyra v.3, p.62"/><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 442.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1426.</ref> Pedro II returned to Brazil and disembarked in Rio de Janeiro on 22 August 1888.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.200">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 200.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1438.</ref> The "whole country welcomed him with an enthusiasm never seen before. From the capital, from the provinces, from everywhere, arrived proofs of affection and veneration."<ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 64.</ref> With the devotion expressed by Brazilians upon the return of the Emperor and the Empress from Europe, the [[monarchy]] seemed to enjoy unshakable support<ref name="Lyra v.3, p.67">[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 67.</ref> and to be at the height of its popularity."<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.200"/><ref name="Vainfas, p.201">[[#refVainfas2002|Vainfas (2002)]], p. 201.</ref><ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 444.</ref>

The nation enjoyed great international prestige during the final years of the Empire<ref name="Topik1996p56">[[#refTopik1996|Topik (1996)]], p. 56.</ref> and it had become an [[Emerging Powers|emerging power]] within the international arena.{{ref label|specialnote_C|C|none}} Predictions of economic and labor disruption caused by the abolition of slavery failed to materialize and the 1888 coffee harvest was successful.<ref name="Barman1999p346">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 346.</ref> The end of slavery had resulted in an explicit shift of support to [[republicanism]] by rich and powerful coffee farmers who held great political, economic and social power in the country,<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 438.</ref><ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 190.</ref> since they regarded emancipation as confiscation of their personal property.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 348<U+2013>349.</ref> To avert a republican backlash, the government exploited the ready credit available to Brazil as a result of its prosperity. It made available massive loans at favorable interest rates to plantation owners and lavishly granted titles and lesser honors to curry favor with influential political figures who had become disaffected.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 351.</ref> The government also indirectly began to address the problem of the recalcitrant military by revitalizing the moribund National Guard, by then an entity which existed mostly only on paper.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 355.</ref>

The measures made by the government alarmed the civilian republicans and the Positivists in the military corps. The republicans saw that it would undercut support for their own aims, and were emboldened to further action.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 353.</ref> The reorganization of the National Guard was begun by the cabinet in August 1889, and the creation of a rival force caused the dissidents among the officer corps to consider desperate steps.<ref name="Barman1999p356">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 356.</ref> For both groups, republicans and military, it had become a case of "now or never".<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], pp. 353, 356.</ref> Although there was no desire in Brazil among the majority of the population to change the [[form of government]],<ref name="Ermakoff2006 p.189"/> republicans began pressuring the Positivists officers to overthrow the monarchy.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 450.</ref>

The Positivists launched a coup and instituted the republic on 15 November 1889.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.360">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 360.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 104.</ref><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.218">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 218.</ref><ref name="Calmon 1975, p.1611">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1611.</ref> The few people who witnessed what occurred did not realize that it was a rebellion.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.459">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 459.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 96.</ref> Historian L<U+00ED>dia Besouchet noted that "Rarely has a revolution been so minor."<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 538.</ref> During the whole ordeal Pedro II showed no emotion, as if unconcerned about the outcome.<ref name="Barman 1999, p.361">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 361.</ref> He dismissed all suggestions for quelling the rebellion which politicians and military leaders put forward.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.217">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]],  p. 217.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 99.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], pp. 1603<U+2013>1604.</ref> When he heard the news of his deposition he simply commented: "If it is so, it will be my retirement. I have worked too hard and I am tired. I will go rest then."<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.218"/> He and his family were sent to exile on 17 November.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.220">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]],  p. 220.</ref>

==Exile and legacy==
===Last years===
{{Main|Exile and death of Pedro II of Brazil}}
[[Image:Pedro II 1891 00.jpg|thumb|left|280px|alt=Photograph showing a white-bearded man, hands folded on stomach, dressed in a uniform with sash and chain of office and lying in state on cushions with a book under the cushion at the head|Pedro II, clad in the court dress uniform of a [[Marshal (Brazil)#Marshals of the Empire of Brazil|Marshal of the Army]], on his bier, 6 December 1891: the book beneath the pillow under his head symbolized that his mind rests upon knowledge even in death]]
There was significant monarchist reaction after the [[Decline and fall of Pedro II of Brazil#Republican coup|fall of the empire]], which was thoroughly repressed.<ref>[[#refSalles1996|Salles (1996)]] , p. 194.</ref> Riots in protest against the coup occurred, as well as pitched battles between monarchist Army troops and republican militias.<ref>[[#refM<U+00F4>naco1986|M<U+00F4>naco Janotti (1986)]], p. 117.</ref> The "new regime suppressed with swift brutality and total disdain for civil liberties all attempts to launch a monarchist party or to publish monarchist newspapers."<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 400.</ref> Empress Teresa Cristina died a few days after their arrival in Europe<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 234.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 371.</ref> and Isabel and her family moved to another place while her father remained in Paris.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 235.</ref><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 377.</ref> His last couple of years were lonely and melancholic, as he lived in modest hotels without money and writing in his journal of dreams in which he was allowed to return to Brazil.<ref>[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 237<U+2013>238.</ref><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 595.</ref><ref>[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], pp. 156<U+2013>157.</ref>

One day he took a long drive in an open carriage along the [[Seine]], even though it was very cold. He felt ill after returning to the hotel that evening.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.238">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 238.</ref><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 27.</ref> The illness progressed into [[pneumonia]] during the following days.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.238"/><ref name="Besouchet, p.29">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 29.</ref> Pedro II rapidly declined and died at 00:35 a.m. on 5 December<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.238-9">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], pp. 238<U+2013>239.</ref><ref name="Schwarcz, p.489">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 489.</ref> surrounded by his family.<ref name="Lyra v.3, p.165">[[#refLyrav3|Lyra (v.3, 1977)]], p. 165.</ref> His last words were, "May God grant me these last wishes<U+2014>peace and prosperity for Brazil..."<ref name="Besouchet, p.30">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 30.</ref> While the body was being prepared, a sealed package in the room was found, and next to it a message written by the Emperor himself: "It is soil from my country, I wish it to be placed in my coffin in case I die away from my fatherland."<ref name="Schwarcz, p.489"/><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1897">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1897.</ref><ref name="Besouchet, p.604">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 604.</ref> The package, which contained earth from every Brazilian province, was duly placed inside the coffin.<ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1897"/><ref name="Besouchet, p.606">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 606.</ref>

Princess Isabel wished to hold a discreet and private burial ceremony.<ref name="Besouchet, p.609">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 609.</ref> However, she eventually accepted the French Government's request for a [[State funeral]].<ref name="Schwarcz, p.489"/><ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.239"/><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1896.</ref> On 9 December, thousands of mourners attended the ceremony at La Madeleine. Aside from Pedro II's family, these included: [[Amadeo of Spain|Amadeo]], former king of Spain; [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]], former king of the Two Sicilies; [[Isabella II of Spain|Isabella II]], former queen of Spain; [[Philippe, comte de Paris]]; and other members of European royalty.<ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1898">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1898.</ref><ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 617.</ref> Also present were General [[Joseph Brug<U+00E8>re]], representing President [[Marie Fran<U+00E7>ois Sadi Carnot|Sadi Carnot]]; the presidents of the [[Senate of France|Senate]] and the [[Chamber of Deputies of France|Chamber of Deputies]]<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.239"/> as well as their members; diplomats; and other representatives of the French government.<ref name="Besouchet, p.618">[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 618.</ref> Nearly all members of the [[Institut de France]] were in attendance.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.239">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 239.</ref><ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1899">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1899.</ref> Other governments from the Americas and Europe also sent representatives, as did distant countries such as [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turkey]], [[Qing Dynasty|China]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] and [[Persia under Qajar dynasty|Persia]].<ref name="Besouchet, p.618"/> Following the services, the coffin was taken in procession to the train station, whence it would travel to [[Portugal]]. Around 300,000<ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1900">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1900.</ref> people lined the route despite incessant rain and cold temperatures.<ref>[[#refBesouchet1993|Besouchet (1993)]], p. 614.</ref> The journey continued on to the [[Monastery of S<U+00E3>o Vicente de Fora|Church of S<U+00E3>o Vicente de Fora]] near [[Lisbon]], where the body of Pedro II was interred in the [[Monastery of S<U+00E3>o Vicente de Fora#Braganza Pantheon|Braganza Pantheon]] on 12 December.<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.240">[[#refCarvalho2007|Carvalho (2007)]], p. 240.</ref><ref>[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], pp. 1900<U+2013>1902.</ref>

The Brazilian republican government, "fearful of a backlash resulting from the death of the emperor", banned any official reaction.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.493">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 493.</ref> Nevertheless, the [[Brazilian people]] were far from indifferent to Pedro II's demise, and "repercussions in Brazil were also immense, despite the government's effort to suppress. There were demonstrations of sorrow throughout the country: shuttered business activity, flags displayed at half-staff, black armbands on clothes, death knells, religious ceremonies."<ref name="Carvalho 2007, p.240"/><ref name="M<U+00F4>naco Janotti, p.50">[[#refM<U+00F4>naco1986|M<U+00F4>naco Janotti (1986)]], p. 50.</ref> Masses were held in memory of Pedro II throughout Brazil, and both he and the monarchy were praised in the eulogies which followed.<ref name="M<U+00F4>naco Janotti, p.50"/>

===Legacy===
{{Main|Legacy of Pedro II of Brazil}}
[[Image:Petropolis-Cathedral4.jpg|thumb|right|220px|alt=Inside a gothic chapel, a marble effigy of a bearded emperor in uniform lies atop an intricately carved stone sarcophagus|Tomb of Pedro II and Teresa Cristina within the Cathedral of Petr<U+00F3>polis]]
After his fall, Brazilians remained attached to the popular Emperor whom they regarded as a hero<ref name="Schwarcz, p.497">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 497.</ref> and continued to perceive him as a national symbol, the Father of the People personified.<ref>[[#refMartins2008|Martins (2008)]], p. 66.</ref> This view was even stronger among those [[Afro-Brazilian|of African descent]], who equated the monarchy with freedom.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 469.</ref> The phenomenon of continued support for the deposed monarch is largely credited to a generally held and unextinguished belief that he was a truly "wise, benevolent, austere and honest ruler."<ref name="Salles 1996, p.15">[[#refSalles1996|Salles (1996)]], p. 15.</ref> The positive view towards Pedro II, and nostalgia for his reign, only grew as the nation quickly fell into a series of economic and political crises which Brazilians attributed to the Emperor's overthrow.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 496.</ref> He never ceased being a popular hero, and would gradually become, once again, an official hero.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.498">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 498.</ref>

Surprisingly strong feelings of guilt were manifested among republicans, and these became increasingly evident upon the Emperor's death in exile at the end of 1891.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], pp. 495<U+2013>496.</ref> They praised Pedro II, who was seen as a model of [[Res publica|republican ideals]],<ref name="Schwarcz, p.508">[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 508.</ref> and the imperial era, which they believed should be regarded as an example to be followed by the young republic.<ref>[[#refMartins2008|Martins (2008)]], p. 123.</ref> In Brazil, the news of the Emperor's death "aroused a genuine sense of regret among those who, without sympathy for a restoration, acknowledged both the merits and the achievements of their deceased ruler."<ref name="Schwarcz, p.497"/><ref name="Salles 1996, p.15"/><ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 402.</ref><ref>[[#refMartins2008|Martins (2008)]], pp. 122<U+2013>123.</ref>

His remains, as well of his wife, were finally returned to Brazil in 1920 and the government granted Pedro II dignities befitting a Head of State.<ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1914">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1914.</ref> A national holiday was declared and the return of the Emperor as a national hero<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 503.</ref> was celebrated throughout the country.<ref name="Schwarcz, p.508"/> Thousands attended the main ceremony in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. Pedro Calmon describes the scene: "elderly people cried. Many knelt down. All clapped hands. There was no distinction between republicans and monarchists. They were all Brazilians."<ref name="Calmon (1975), p.1915">[[#refCalmon1975|Calmon (1975)]], p. 1915.</ref> This homage marked the reconciliation of Republican Brazil with its monarchical past.<ref>[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 405.</ref>

Historians have expressed high regard for Pedro II and his reign. The scholarly literature dealing with him is vast and, with the exception of the period immediately after his ouster, overwhelmingly positive, and even laudatory.<ref>[[#refSchwarcz1998|Schwarcz (1998)]], p. 22.</ref> Emperor Pedro II is usually regarded by historians in Brazil as the greatest Brazilian.<ref name="Bueno, p.196"/><ref name="Vianna1994 p.467">[[#refVianna1994|Vianna1994 (1994)]], p. 467.</ref><ref name="Benevides1979 p.61">[[#refBenevides1979|Benevides (1979)]], p. 61.</ref> In a manner quite similar to methods which had been used by republicans, historians point to the Emperor's virtues as an example to be followed, although none go so far as to advocate a restoration of the monarchy. Richard Graham notes: "Most twentieth-century historians, moreover, have looked back on the period [of Pedro II's reign] nostalgically, using their descriptions of the Empire to criticize<U+2014>sometimes subtly, sometimes not<U+2014>Brazil's subsequent republican or dictatorial regimes."<ref>[[#refGraham1994|Graham (1994)]], p. 4.</ref>

==Titles and honors==
{{Infobox Royal styles
| image      = [[Image:Brazilimperialblason2.svg|55px|alt=Coat of arms consisting of a shield with a green field with a golden armillary sphere over the red and white Cross of the Order of Christ, surrounded by a blue band with 20 silver stars; the bearers are two arms of a wreath, with a coffee branch on the left and a flowering tobacco branch on the right; and above the shield is an arched golden and jeweled crown]]
| royal name = Pedro II, Emperor of Brazil
| dipstyle   = [[Imperial Majesty (style)|His Imperial Majesty]]
| offstyle   = Your Imperial Majesty
| altstyle   = Sire
}}

===Titles and styles===

* 2 December 1825 <U+2013> 7 April 1831: ''His Imperial Highness'' The Prince Imperial
* 7 April 1831 <U+2013> 15 November 1889: ''His Imperial Majesty'' The Emperor

The Emperor's full style and title were:{{cquote|His Imperial Majesty Dom Pedro II, Constitutional Emperor and Perpetual Defender of Brazil.<ref>[[#refRodrigues1863|Rodrigues (1863)]], p. 71.</ref>}}

===Honors===
[[File:Monogram of Peter II.svg|thumb|right|200px|alt=A design in gold on a green field, consisting of the letters P, I, I, within a circlet of 20 stars, and surrounded by a wreath with a branch of coffee on the left and tobacco on the right, and an arched crown at the top|Monogram of D. Pedro II]]
Emperor Pedro II was Grand Master (Sovereign) of the following Brazilian Orders: 

* [[Order of Christ (Brazil)|Order of Christ]].<ref name="Barman1999 p.11">[[#refBarman1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 11.</ref>
* [[Order of Saint Benedict of Aviz]].<ref name="Barman1999 p.11"/>
* [[Order of Saint James of the Sword]].<ref name="Barman1999 p.11"/>
* [[Order of the Southern Cross]].<ref name="Barman1999 p.11"/>
* [[Order of Pedro I]].<ref name="Barman1999 p.11"/>
* [[Order of the Rose]].<ref name="Barman1999 p.11"/>

He was a recipient  of the following foreign honors:

* Grand Cross of the Austro-Hungarian [[Order of Saint Stephen of Hungary|Order of Saint Stephen]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41">[[#refSauer1889|Sauer (1889)]], p. 41.</ref>
* Grand Cordon of the Belgian [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Romanian [[Order of the Star of Romania|Order of the Star]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Knight of the Danish [[Order of the Elephant]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the [[Order of Saint Januarius]] of the Two Sicilies.<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the [[Order of Saint Ferdinand and of Merit]] of the Two Sicilies.<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the French [[L<U+00E9>gion d'honneur]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Greek [[Order of the Redeemer]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Dutch [[Order of the Netherlands Lion]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Spanish [[Order of the Golden Fleece]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Stranger Knight of the British [[Order of the Garter]].<ref>[[#refBegent1999|Begent (1999)]], p. 212.</ref>
* Grand Cross of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Order of Malta]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Portuguese [[Order of the Immaculate Conception of Vila Vi<U+00E7>osa]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Portuguese [[Order of the Tower and Sword]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Prussian [[Order of the Black Eagle]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of all Russian orders of chivalry.<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Italian [[Order of the Most Holy Annunciation]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Swedish [[Royal Order of the Seraphim]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross of the Swedish [[Order of the Polar Star]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>
* Grand Cross (First Class) of the Turkish [[Order of the Medjidie]].<ref name="Sauer1889 p.41"/>

