==See also==
{{Commons category}}
*[[Politics of the Empire of Brazil]]

==Endnotes==
<ol style="list-style:upper-alpha"><li>{{note label|specialnote_A|A|none}} "The Second Reign, that is, the period in which our Emperor was D. Pedro II, lasted fifty-eight years, from the abdication of his father, D. Pedro I, in 1831, until the proclamation of the republic in 1889." <U+2014>H<U+00E9>lio Vianna<ref>[[#refVianna1994|Vianna (1994)]], p. 467.</ref></li>
<li>{{note label|specialnote_B|B|none}} "The peace was concluded and allowed, with the implementation of his ideals, the evolution of democracy in Brazil. There is not a more continuous period of tranquility in the history of South America, so different than the experiences of Brazil's neighbors [the South American republics formerly ruled by Spain] that J.B. Alberdi considered this the 'Brazilian miracle'. When the throne fell in 1889, [[Juan Pablo Rojas Pa<U+00FA>l|Rojas Pa<U+00FA>l]], president of Venezuela, said, 'It has ended the only republic that existed in [South] America: the Empire of Brazil.' [[Bartolom<U+00E9> Mitre|Mitre]] called it 'a crowned democracy'." <U+2014>Pedro Calmon<ref>[[#refCalmon2002|Calmon (2002)]], p. 217.</ref></li>
<li>{{note label|specialnote_C|C|none}} Historian Roderick J. Barman says that opinion of Brazil's growing importance was widely shared by other nations.<ref>[[#refBarman 1999|Barman (1999)]], p. 306.</ref> See also, [[Decline and fall of Pedro II of Brazil#Decline|Decline and fall of Pedro II]] for further details.</li></ol>

